The Ego Trick (Julian Baggini)
- Your Highlight on page 10 | location 141-144 | Added on Sunday, 20 November 2016 02:14:27

This point is worth stressing. One of the cheapest and most effective rhetorical tricks in the book is the use of the debunking ‘just’ or ‘mere’. Many perfectly sound ideas can be made to appear quite implausible by the judicious insertion of one of these words. Critics deny that thought is ‘merely’ the product of brain function, that human beings are ‘just’ biological machines, or that music is ‘nothing more than’ the vibration of air. Take away the words in scare-quotes, however, and what is so outrageous about any of these statements?
